<file path="YourNote-101:-Software-Quality-Characteristics.md">
## What Are Software Quality Characteristics?
Software Quality Characteristics describe how good a software product is from the perspectives of users, developers, and stakeholders — not just whether it works, but how well it works.


## The 8 Core Software Quality Characteristics (ISO/IEC 25010)
https://iso25000.com/en/iso-25000-standards/iso-25010

#### 1. Functional Suitability
Does the software do what it is supposed to do?
- Functional completeness
- Functional correctness
- Functional appropriateness

📌 Example:
An e-commerce system correctly calculates total price, tax, and discounts.


#### 2. Performance Efficiency
How fast and resource-efficient is the system?
- Response time
- Throughput
- Resource utilization

📌 Example:
API responds within 2 seconds for 10,000 users.


#### 3. Compatibility
Can the software work with other systems?
- Co-existence
- Interoperability

📌 Example:
Your Spring Boot API integrates smoothly with an Angular frontend and third-party payment gateway.


#### 4. Usability
How easy is the software to learn and use?
- Learnability
- Operability
- User error protection
- Accessibility

📌 Example:
First-time users can submit a paper in a CMS without training.


#### 5. Reliability
Does the system work consistently over time?
- Maturity
- Availability
- Fault tolerance
- Recoverability

📌 Example:
System auto-recovers after server crash without data loss.


#### 6. Security
How well does the system protect data and access?
- Confidentiality
- Integrity
- Accountability
- Authenticity

📌 Example:
JWT authentication, role-based access (Admin, Reviewer, Author).


#### 7. Maintainability
How easy is it to modify and fix the system?
- Modularity
- Reusability
- Analysability
- Modifiability
- Testability

📌 Example:
Bug fix in one module does not break the entire system.


#### 8. Portability
How easily can the software move across environments?
- Adaptability
- Installability
- Replaceability

📌 Example:
Application runs the same on local machine, Docker, and cloud.


#### Why These Characteristics Matter?
| Stakeholder   | Cares Most About                    |
| ------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| Users         | Usability, Reliability, Performance |
| Developers    | Maintainability, Testability        |
| Security Team | Security                            |
| Management    | Reliability, Cost efficiency        |
| DevOps        | Portability, Performance            |


#### Mapping to SQA Activities
| Quality Characteristic | SQA Activity                            |
| ---------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| Functional Suitability | Requirement reviews, functional testing |
| Performance Efficiency | Load & stress testing                   |
| Usability              | User testing, UI reviews                |
| Reliability            | Fault injection, recovery testing       |
| Security               | Penetration testing, access control     |
| Maintainability        | Code reviews, unit tests                |
| Portability            | Dockerization, CI/CD pipelines          |
</file>

<file path="YourNote-201:-McCall-Model.md">
## What Is the McCall Software Quality Model?
- The McCall Model (1977) is one of the earliest software quality models. It was designed to bridge the gap between users and developers by translating quality concerns into measurable technical factors.
- The McCall software quality model classifies software quality into product operation, revision, and transition factors to systematically evaluate quality attributes from both user and developer perspectives.


## Structure of the McCall Model (11 Factors)

### 1. Product Operation Factors (5 Factors)
How well the software works for users during operation
| Factor          | Meaning                                  |
| --------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| **Correctness** | Meets requirements and specifications    |
| **Reliability** | Performs consistently without failure    |
| **Efficiency**  | Uses resources (CPU, memory) effectively |
| **Integrity**   | Protects data from unauthorized access   |
| **Usability**   | Easy to learn and use                    |
📌 User-centered view


### 2. Product Revision Factors (3 Factors)
How easy it is to change and maintain the software
| Factor              | Meaning                      |
| ------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| **Maintainability** | Easy to fix defects          |
| **Flexibility**     | Easy to modify for new needs |
| **Testability**     | Easy to test and validate    |
📌 Developer & maintenance view


### 3. Product Transition Factors (3 Factors)
How easily software adapts to new environments
| Factor               | Meaning                     |
| -------------------- | --------------------------- |
| **Portability**      | Runs on different platforms |
| **Reusability**      | Components can be reused    |
| **Interoperability** | Works with other systems    |
📌 Long-term & organizational view


## Why McCall Model Is Important?
| Reason                     | Explanation                       |
| -------------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| First formal quality model | Foundation for later models       |
| Developer-friendly         | Easy to understand                |
| Measurement-oriented       | Encourages metrics                |
| Still exam-relevant        | Frequently asked in theory papers |


## Limitations of the McCall Model
| Limitation                 | Explanation                                |
| -------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| Outdated                   | Created before modern web & mobile systems |
| No explicit security depth | Compared to modern standards               |
| No process focus           | Product-based only                         |
| No usability accessibility | Lacks modern UX concepts                   |


## McCall vs Modern Models
| Aspect          | McCall Model    | ISO/IEC 25010             |
| --------------- | --------------- | ------------------------- |
| Year            | 1977            | 2011                      |
| Focus           | Product quality | Product + user experience |
| Security        | Integrity only  | Full security model       |
| Maintainability | Yes             | Yes (more detailed)       |
| Relevance       | Conceptual      | Industry standard         |
</file>

<file path="YourNote-301:-CMMI.md">
## 1. What is CMMI?

**CMMI (Capability Maturity Model Integration)** is a framework used to improve an organization's processes, quality, productivity, and project management practices. CMMI was developed by the Software Engineering Institute (SEI) at Carnegie Mellon University.

---

## 2. Why is CMMI Important?

Organizations use CMMI to:

- Improve software quality
- Deliver projects on time
- Reduce development costs
- Increase process maturity
- Support continuous improvement

---

## 3. CMMI Maturity Levels

CMMI defines **5 Maturity Levels**.

### Level 1 – Initial

#### Characteristics

- Processes are ad hoc and chaotic
- Success depends on individual effort
- No standard procedures

#### Example

- Developers work differently on every project
- Documentation is inconsistent

---

### Level 2 – Managed

#### Characteristics

- Basic project management practices exist
- Requirements are tracked
- Project planning is performed

#### Example

- Project schedules are created
- Risks are identified
- Progress is monitored

---

### Level 3 – Defined

#### Characteristics

- Organization-wide standard processes
- Processes are documented and standardized
- Best practices are shared

#### Example

- Every project follows the same development methodology
- Standard templates are used

---

### Level 4 – Quantitatively Managed

#### Characteristics

- Processes are measured using statistical techniques
- Performance is predictable

#### Example

- Defect rates are analyzed
- Productivity metrics are monitored
- Quality goals are measured

---

### Level 5 – Optimizing

#### Characteristics

- Continuous process improvement
- Innovation and defect prevention
- Root cause analysis

#### Example

- Continuous improvement programs
- Automation initiatives
- Lessons learned incorporated into processes

---

## 4. CMMI Maturity Level Summary

| Level | Name | Focus |
|---------|---------|---------|
| 1 | Initial | Ad hoc processes |
| 2 | Managed | Basic project management |
| 3 | Defined | Standardized organizational processes |
| 4 | Quantitatively Managed | Metrics and statistical control |
| 5 | Optimizing | Continuous improvement |

---

## 5. CMMI vs ISO 9001

| Aspect | CMMI | ISO 9001 |
|----------|----------|----------|
| Purpose | Process improvement | Quality management system |
| Focus | Software and systems processes | Organization-wide quality |
| Assessment | Maturity levels | Certification |
| Levels | 1–5 | No maturity levels |
| Goal | Process capability improvement | Compliance with standards |

---

## 6. CMMI and Software Quality Management

CMMI supports Software Quality Management through:

### Quality Assurance

- Process audits
- Compliance checks
- Process improvement

### Quality Control

- Defect tracking
- Testing
- Reviews and inspections

### Measurement

- Defect density
- Productivity
- Customer satisfaction
- Schedule performance

